<br>
Although it is always a good idea to act &quot;for the good of the guild&quot; if you get to a point where you're resenting the good of the guild, it's time to think of the &quot;good of you.&quot;--and playing more, I don't care who you are, is not going to help you.<br>
<br>
I see a certain irony in watching a person who quit playing and sold their character argue about the merit of &quot;hardcore&quot; playing.<br>
<br>
How many people do you know who quit your guild (whatever guild that may be) moved to another, because they wanted to be more &quot;hardcore&quot; and then, in a few months, quit the game? Maybe I know the wrong people but I'd go with about 50%...and the ones that lasted? They knew when to stop with the drama.<br>
<br>
Drama can be fun and exciting, I generally have to moderate my love of a good drama with my desire to not emotionally scar people.<br>
<br>
A good litmus test for an EQ drama: if you can explain it to someone who doesn't play EQ (if you don't know anyone like that...well then--that's another indication isnt it?)--and have them Not think you're being stupid, then maybe you have a point. Maybe.<br>
<br>
Re: Fam--be ok you all in it and out. I think you'll be pleasantly surprised to see that you don't need numbers to accomplish things...just keep an even keel.<br>
